      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">This report details the second annual, full-day workshop exploring
                the metrology necessary for repeatably and independently assessing the performance
                of robotic systems in real-world human-robot interaction (HRI) scenarios. This
                workshop continues the motion toward bridging the gaps between the theory and
                applications of HRI, enabling reproducible studies in HRI, and accelerating the
                adoption of cutting-edge technologies as the industry state-of-practice. The second
                annual workshop, 'Test Methods and Metrics for Effective HRI', seeks to identify
                test methods and metrics for the holistic assessment and assurance of HRI
                performance in practical applications. The focus is on identifying the key
                performance indicators of seemingly disparate sectors, and to foster the community
                based on the principles of transparency, repeatability and reproducibility, and
                establishing trust. The goal is to aid in the advancement of HRI technologies
                through the development of experimental design, test methods, and metrics for
                assessing HRI and interface designs.</abstract>
